---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import PtoPayoutCalculator from '../../components/calculator/PtoPayoutCalculator.astro';
import Card from '../../components/ui/Card.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { label: 'Home', path: '/' },
  { label: 'Calculators', path: '/all-calculators' },
  { label: 'PTO Payout Calculator', path: '/calculator/pto-payout-calculator' }
];
---

<Layout
  title="PTO Payout Calculator - Calculate Unused Vacation Cash-Out & Taxes"
  description="Free online PTO Payout Calculator. Calculate unused vacation hours, salaried hourly equivalents, company policy caps, supplemental taxes, and net take-home cash."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <div class="calculator-page-container container">
    <!-- Interactive Component Slot -->
    <PtoPayoutCalculator />

    <!-- Guide Content Section -->
    <div class="calculator-guide-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-12);">
      
      <!-- Prominent Blog Post Cross-Link Card -->
      <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <Card elevation="sm" style="border: 1.5px solid var(--color-primary); background-color: var(--color-bg-base); padding: var(--space-5);">
          <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-primary); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Featured PTO Resignation Case Study</span>
            <h3 style="margin: 0; font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 800;">The Resignation Reality Check: How My $4,300 PTO Payout Turned Into $2,800</h3>
            <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); line-height: 1.5;">
              Read the first-person story of a tech designer who resigned expecting a $4,300 cash check for 120 unused PTO hours, only to face company policy caps and a 35% supplemental wage tax deduction.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog/calculate-pto-payout-leaving-job" style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-primary); margin-top: var(--space-2); display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 4px; width: fit-content; text-decoration: underline;">
              Read: How to Calculate PTO Payouts When Leaving a Job & State Laws
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
        </Card>
      </div>

      <div class="prose">
        <h2>What is a PTO Payout?</h2>
        <p>
          In employment law, payroll accounting, and personal finance, a <strong>PTO payout</strong> (Paid Time Off payout) is the financial compensation an employee receives for their accrued, unused vacation hours or sick leave. A PTO cash-out usually occurs when an employee resigns, is terminated, retires, or exercises an annual company voluntary cash-out option.
        </p>
        <p>
          While accrued vacation time represents earned wages in many jurisdictions, payout rules vary dramatically depending on your state labor laws, employment contracts, and company policy caps.
        </p>

        <h2>How This Calculator Works (Step-by-Step)</h2>
        <p>
          To compute your gross PTO cash-out, tax deductions, and net take-home pay, follow these steps:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Select Your Currency:</strong> Choose your local currency from the dropdown menu (e.g. USD, EUR, INR) to format all input fields and results correctly.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Select Compensation Type:</strong> Choose between Hourly Wage Employee or Salaried Employee.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Input Wage & Salary Parameters:</strong> If hourly, enter your Base Hourly Wage. If salaried, enter your Annual Base Salary and standard weekly work hours (typically 40 hours) to calculate your effective hourly wage.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Input PTO Hours Balance:</strong> Enter your Total Accrued PTO Hours and any Already Used PTO Hours to isolate your net unused balance.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Configure Company Policy & Taxes:</strong> Input your Company Payout Rate % (usually 100%), any Max Payout Hour Cap (enter 0 for unlimited), and your estimated Supplemental Tax Rate % (typically 22% federal + state/FICA).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Review Output Metrics:</strong> The calculator instantly displays your gross PTO payout, net take-home cash, payable hours, and tax deductions.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>The Mathematics of PTO Payouts</h2>
        <p>
          The calculator applies corporate accounting formulas to process your cash-out metrics:
        </p>
        
        <h3>1. Salaried Hourly Wage Equivalent Formula</h3>
        <p>
          If you earn an annual salary, your employer converts your salary into an equivalent hourly wage rate:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Hourly Wage} = \\frac{\\text{Annual Base Salary}}{\\text{Weekly Work Hours} \\times 52}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, a $75,000 annual salary based on a standard 40-hour workweek yields an hourly wage of:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Hourly Wage} = \\frac{\\$75,000}{40 \\times 52} = \\frac{\\$75,000}{2,080} = \\mathbf{\\$36.06 \\text{ / hour}}\\)"}
        </p>

        <h3>2. Net Unused & Payable PTO Hours</h3>
        <p>
          First, calculate your remaining unused PTO balance:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Unused PTO Hours} = \\text{Total Accrued Hours} - \\text{Already Used Hours}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          Next, apply any company payout caps (C) and payout rates (R%):
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Payable Hours} = \\min(\\text{Unused PTO Hours}, \\text{Cap (C)}) \\times \\frac{\\text{Payout Rate (R)}}{100}\\)"}
        </p>

        <h3>3. Gross PTO Payout & Net Take-Home Cash</h3>
        <p>
          Your gross cash-out is calculated by multiplying payable hours by your hourly wage:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Gross PTO Payout} = \\text{Payable Hours} \\times \\text{Hourly Wage}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          Because PTO payouts upon job separation are often classified as supplemental wages by tax authorities, they are subject to flat withholding rates (T%):
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Net Take-Home Cash} = \\text{Gross PTO Payout} \\times (1 - \\frac{\\text{Supplemental Tax Rate (T)}}{100})\\)"}
        </p>

        <h2>Example Scenario Analysis</h2>
        <p>
          Suppose an hourly employee earns $35.00/hr. They accrued 80 hours of PTO and used 20 hours, leaving 60 unused PTO hours. Their company pays out 100% of unused PTO with no cap. The estimated supplemental tax rate is 25%.
        </p>
        <p>
          The calculator will compute:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Unused PTO Hours:</strong> {"\\(80 - 20 = \\mathbf{60.00 \\text{ hours}}\\)"} (equivalent to 7.50 workdays)
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Gross PTO Payout:</strong> {"\\(60 \\text{ hours} \\times \\$35.00 = \\mathbf{\\$2,100.00}\\)"}
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Estimated Tax Withholdings (25%):</strong> {"\\(\\$2,100.00 \\times 0.25 = \\mathbf{\\$525.00}\\)"}
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Net Take-Home Cash:</strong> {"\\(\\$2,100.00 - \\$525.00 = \\mathbf{\\$1,575.00}\\)"}
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>State PTO Payout Laws (United States)</h2>
        <p>
          Whether your employer is legally obligated to pay out unused PTO when you leave depends heavily on your state:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Mandatory Payout States:</strong> In states like California, Illinois, Montana, and Nebraska, earned vacation time is legally considered vested wages. Employers are strictly prohibited from implementing "use-it-or-lose-it" policies and must pay out 100% of accrued, unused PTO on your final paycheck.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Policy-Dependent States:</strong> In states like New York, Texas, and Florida, employers are only required to pay out unused PTO if their written employee handbook or employment contract explicitly promises to do so.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Use-It-or-Lose-It Permitted States:</strong> In certain states, employers can establish policies where unused PTO is forfeited at the end of the calendar year or upon separation if not used.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div class="calculator-faq-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-10); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: var(--space-8);">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">PTO Payout FAQs</h2>
        
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-4);">
          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);" open>
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Is an employer legally required to pay out unused PTO when you leave a job?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              It depends on your state laws and employment contract. In states like California, Illinois, and Montana, employers are legally required to pay out 100% of accrued unused PTO upon separation. In other states, payout depends strictly on company policy outlined in your handbook.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">How is a PTO payout calculated for salaried employees?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              For salaried workers, divide your annual base salary by your annual work hours (typically 2,080 hours for a 40-hour workweek) to find your hourly wage rate. Then multiply this hourly rate by your total payable unused PTO hours.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">How is PTO payout taxed compared to regular paychecks?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              When paid out as a lump sum upon separation, the IRS often classifies PTO payouts as <strong>supplemental wages</strong>. Supplemental wages are subject to a flat federal withholding rate of <strong>22%</strong> (plus state taxes and FICA), resulting in higher initial tax deductions on that check.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">What is a "use-it-or-lose-it" PTO policy?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              A "use-it-or-lose-it" policy requires employees to use their accrued vacation hours by a specific date (usually the end of the year) or forfeit them without financial compensation. Some states outlaw these policies, requiring earned PTO to roll over or be paid out.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Can a company cap the maximum number of PTO hours they pay out?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Yes. Many company handbooks specify a maximum cap on PTO payouts (for example, capping payouts at 40 or 80 hours), even if an employee has accrued 150 hours. Unless state law prohibits caps, the company contract governs the payout limit.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .calculator-page-container {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-4);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose h3 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-top: var(--space-5);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .prose ul, .prose ol {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
